# Privacy Notice

This notice describes, in plain language, how vkXtract handles data in its normal local-use workflow.

## 1. Local-first design

vkXtract is designed primarily as a local browser extension workflow.

In normal use, the extension stores working data locally in the browser extension environment so that the user can review targets, reopen cases, and export packages.

## 2. Data the extension may store locally

Depending on how you use the tool, vkXtract may store locally:

- the VK access token you paste into the extension
- active target/case identifiers
- extracted VK API response data
- per-target case bundles
- task state and extraction metadata
- local caches used by report workflows
- exported report/package content that you explicitly choose to save

## 3. External services the extension may contact

vkXtract may communicate with external services needed for its workflows, including:

- VK pages and VK API endpoints
- VK-related media/CDN endpoints where relevant to extraction or packaging
- OpenStreetMap tile services for map display
- Nominatim/OpenStreetMap geocoding where that workflow is used

vkXtract is not designed as a general telemetry product and does not require a dedicated vendor backend for ordinary local case use.

## 4. Token handling

The VK access token is user-supplied.

You are responsible for:

- obtaining it lawfully
- deciding whether to paste it into the extension
- protecting it from exposure
- clearing it when no longer needed
- revoking it at VK if it is compromised

## 5. Case data and exports

Case data may remain stored locally until you delete it.

Exports such as raw JSON, report packages, and media-related files are stored where you choose to save them.

Once exported, those files are under your control and responsibility.

## 6. Deletion and cleanup

Depending on the workflow, vkXtract provides controls to:

- reset the current target
- delete the current stored target
- delete all stored targets
- remove locally stored token data

You can also uninstall the extension.

If you no longer want a VK token to remain usable, revoke it at the VK side as well.

## 7. User responsibility

You are responsible for determining whether your use of vkXtract involves:

- personal data
- special-category or sensitive material
- workplace records
- regulated data
- disclosure obligations
- retention/deletion obligations

You are also responsible for applying any encryption, access control, retention, disclosure, or deletion controls required by your environment.

## 8. Changes

This notice may change between releases as the tool evolves.

Users should review the legal and privacy documentation that ships with the specific release they are using.
